04969nam a2200565Ia 9781978834156DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97819788341567 a10.36019/97819788341562doi  a(DE-B1597)680068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDA125.S57bR38 2024 7aSPO0000002bisacsh04a305.48/8914041223/eng/202312081 aRatna, Aarti, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Nation of Family and Friends? :bSport and the Leisure Cultures of British Asian Girls and Women /cAarti Ratna. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (163 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Sport and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Sibling Rivalries -- tIntroduction: A Sporting Nation of Family and Friends? -- t1. The Making of the “South Asian Woman” -- t2. Walking with Friends and Family -- t3. Gendering the Racial Production of Sporting Films -- t4. The Politics of Sporting Conviviality -- tConclusion: South Asian Women, Mothers, Workers, Lovers, Players, Fans, and Friends -- tEpilogue: An Antiracist Feminist Tool Kit -- tAcknowledgments -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn A Nation of Family and Friends, sociologist Aarti Ratna examines the complex and dynamic relationships between South Asian women and sporting and leisure cultures. Mining autobiographical insights (as a South Asian scholar living in the UK) she links the chapters of this innovative book using the sociological concepts of family and friends, particularly as they relate to an analysis of wider debates about the complexities of race, gender, and the nation. Ratna underscores the importance of studying informal spaces of sport and leisure as friendly, familial, sociable, and political spaces. She simultaneously highlights the role of earlier sociological research in disseminating myths about South Asian women as too physically weak to play competitive sports; culturally passive victims of South Asian cultures and religions; and as sexually exotic women requiring saving through colonial and imperial projects led by white men and women. Ratna also examines two key cultural objects - the popular films "Bend it Like Beckham" and “Dhan Dhana Dhan Goal” - to examine in detail the gendered representation of South Asian soccer players’ engagement in amateur and elite levels of the sport. She critiques studies of women’s football fandom and sport that fail to acknowledge social differences relating to race, class, age, disability, and sexuality. By linking the social forces (across time and space) that differentially affect their sporting choices and leisure lifestyles, Ratna portrays the women of the South Asian diaspora as active agents in the shaping of their life courses and as skilled navigators of the complexities affecting their own identities. Ultimately Ratna examines the intersections of class, caste, age, generation, gender, and sexuality, to provide a rich and critical exploration of British Asian women's sport and leisure choices, pleasures, and lived realities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSouth AsianszGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 0aSouth AsianszGreat BritainxSocial life and customs. 0aSports for girlsxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aSports for womenxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aWomenzGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh  awomen, gender, girls, female, sports, south asian, asian, immigrant, emigrant, culture, sociology, Bend it Like Beckham, Dhan Dhana Dhan Goal, media, pop culture, soccer, football, popular cultu